\subtree{
\title{CRDT Skill - Conflict-free Replicated Data Types}
\p{\strong{Status}: ✅ Production Ready \strong{Framework}: Jules Hedges' Compositional Game Theory \strong{Language}: Ruby (HedgesOpenGames module) \strong{Trit}: ±1 (covariant/contravariant) \strong{Integration}: Amp, Codex, Music-Topos CRDT}

\subtree{
\title{bmorphism Contributions}
\blockquote{*"all is bidirectional"* — [@bmorphism](https://gist.github.com/bmorphism/ead83aec97dab7f581d49ddcb34a46d4), Play/Coplay gist}

\blockquote{*"Automerge is a local-first sync engine for multiplayer apps that works offline, prevents conflicts, and runs fast."* — [Automerge](https://automerge.org/)}

\p{\strong{Plurigrid Connection}: CRDTs embody the principle of \strong{autopoietic ergodicity} — self-sustaining distributed systems that explore all accessible states and converge automatically. This aligns with bmorphism's vision of:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Local-first} computing (offline-capable, no single point of failure)}
\li{\strong{Bidirectional sync} (Play/Coplay structure for state transfer)}
\li{\strong{Conflict-free} composition (open games with guaranteed Nash equilibria)}
}

\p{\strong{Key References}:}

\ul{
\li{[Automerge](https://github.com/automerge/automerge) - JSON-like CRDTs for offline-first apps}
\li{[Yjs](https://yjs.dev/) - High-performance CRDT framework}
\li{[Compositional Game Theory](https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.04641) - Open games foundation for Play/Coplay}
}

\p{Related to bmorphism's work on:}

\ul{
\li{[plurigrid/act](https://github.com/plurigrid/act) - cognitive category theory with eventual consistency}
\li{Parametrised optics for bidirectional state transfer}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{The CRDT Skill provides conflict-free replicated data types with bidirectional lens optics for compositional game theory. It implements core CRDT types with full merge semantics and property verification.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Features}
\subtree{
\title{Core CRDT Types}
\ol{
\li{\strong{LWW Register} (Last-Write-Wins)}
\li{Timestamp-based value ordering}
\li{Simple conflict resolution}
\li{Use case: Simple mutable state}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{G-Counter} (Grow-only Counter)}
\li{Monotonically increasing counts}
\li{Distributed increment operations}
\li{Use case: Metrics and counters}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{PN-Counter} (Positive-Negative Counter)}
\li{Both increment and decrement}
\li{Composed from two G-Counters}
\li{Use case: Inventory, balance tracking}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{OR-Set} (Observed-Remove Set)}
\li{Unordered collection with add/remove}
\li{Unique ID tagging for removal}
\li{Use case: Group membership, tags}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Text CRDT} (Character-based)}
\li{Vector clock causality tracking}
\li{Collaborative text editing}
\li{Use case: Distributed text documents}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Verified Properties}
\p{All CRDTs verify these mathematical properties:}

\ul{
\li{✓ \strong{Idempotence}: merge(A, A) = A}
\li{✓ \strong{Commutativity}: merge(A, B) = merge(B, A)}
\li{✓ \strong{Associativity}: merge(merge(A,B),C) = merge(A,merge(B,C))}
\li{✓ \strong{Causality}: Vector clocks maintain partial order}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Open Games Interface}
\pre{\startverb
# Forward pass (play)
result = skill.play(
  crdt_name: "state",
  operations: [{op: :set, value: 100}],
  strategy: :sequential
)

# Backward pass (coplay)
ack = skill.coplay(
  transfer_id: result[:transfer_id],
  acknowledged: true,
  consistency_verified: true
)
\stopverb}
}

